&gt;
&gt;     &gt;     When unit testing guis you need to get access to the
&gt;     &gt; components in the
&gt;     &gt; view. If you develop under Borlands tool, you get default
&gt;     &gt; access to the
&gt;     &gt; graphical components on the protected level. As in VAJ
&gt;     &gt; the components are
&gt;     &gt; private I have to use reflection to gain access to them.
&gt;
&gt; I argue that there is generally a better way of testing the GUI than this.
&gt; A real separation of model and view should allow for state-access methods
&gt; that return some account of the state of the gui via states of it&#39;s
internal
&gt; parts (usually in composite form).
&gt;
&gt; For instance, if I have a GUI that watches a directory and does some type
of
&gt; processing on the things that come into that directory I might have the
&gt; following:
&gt;
&gt; public class FileProcessorGUI{
&gt; private java.awt.List filesList
&gt; ...other private memebers...
&gt;
&gt; ...ctor&#39;s...
&gt;
&gt; public boolean isProcessing(){
&gt; return directoryField.getText() != null &&
&gt; !directoryField.getText().equals(&quot;&quot;) &&
&gt; filesList.getItemCount() &gt; 0;
&gt; }
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; The isProcessing() method of course reflects that the processing is
&gt; happening if all of the GUI elements meet this criteria, therefore you
must
&gt; have some firing mechanism that would make sure that if this state were
true
&gt; the processing really would happen.
&gt;
&gt; -Jason
